<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1516,1938]" pageId="2" pageNumber="44">
SEM (
<figureCitation box="[260,375,1516,1542]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 9–14" captionStart-1="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId-0="3.[136,243,947,969]" captionStartId-1="3.[136,243,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox-0="[177,1411,190,923]" captionTargetBox-1="[170,1417,1067,1970]" captionTargetId-0="figure-24@3.[177,1411,190,923]" captionTargetId-1="figure-91@3.[170,1417,1067,1970]" captionTargetPageId-0="3" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionText-0="FIGURES 9–14. Stauroneis lacuspowaiensis Wadmare &amp; B.Karthick nom. nov., stat. nov., SEM, external valve views. 9, 10. External views of an entire valve. 11, 13. Terminal raphe fissures continuing on mantle. 12. Stauros with straight central raphe ends. 14. Irregularly placed areolae (double arrowheads). Scale bars = 4 µm (Figs 9, 10, 12); 1 µm (Figs 11, 13, 14)." captionText-1="FIGURES 15–18. Stauroneis lacuspowaiensis Wadmare &amp; B.Karthick nom. nov., stat. nov., SEM, internal valve views. 15. Internal view of an entire valve. 15, 17. Elevated stauros possessing tunnel gap (arrowheads). 17.Areolae irregular covered with hymen structures (double arrowheads). 16, 18. Terminal raphe fissures with helictoglossae. Scale bars = 4 µm (Figs 15–18)." pageId="2" pageNumber="44">Figs 9–18</figureCitation>
): Externally (
